Produce TWO things for this feature:

1. `cases` — structured test design. Rules:
   - Write AT LEAST ONE case per requirement (anchor + independent). For anchor: copy canonical I/O exactly
     (inputs_json = example_inputs_json, expected_json = expected_return_json, oracle = "eq").
   - For INDEPENDENT cases (2-4 per requirement): derive from the precondition/stimulus/response/postcondition.
     Example triggers: boundary values, variant types (empty list, null fields), different precondition states,
     partial/malformed inputs that violate precondition (→ failure case).
   - NEVER invent types or violate the contract. If the contract says "list of ints", not "list of strings."
   - Add failure case ONLY when failure_inputs_json is non-empty. Copy it verbatim as inputs_json,
     oracle = "raises", and set expected_json to
{% if stack == 'fastapi' %}     '{"raises": "HTTPException"}' (a precondition failure surfaces as an HTTP 4xx).
{% else %}     '{"raises": "ValueError"}'.
{% endif %}   - `inputs` / `expected`: short human-readable summaries only.
{% if stack == 'fastapi' %}   - SETUP (Arrange) — this is a REAL web app whose database starts EMPTY. If a case needs data to
     already exist (editing/deleting/cancelling/reading an entity), you MUST establish it via
     `setup_json`: a JSON array of prior calls that create that data through the API, replayed
     before the main call against the same database. Each item is {"inputs": <body-object>} (add
     "route": "<endpoint>" only to hit a DIFFERENT requirement's endpoint). The seed call and the
     main call MUST use the SAME value of the requirement's Entity identifier field (shown above)
     so the lookup finds the row — if the identifier is "name", the add and the edit/delete must
